> A piece of data for carb icing fanatics:
>
> Carb icing does not require cold temperatures and in fact cannot occur at
temperatures below freezing.  As air goes through a carburator
> it is sent through a venturi which increases the speed of the air and,
courtesy of Daniel Bernoulli, lowers the pressure.  Lower pressure,
> according to another chap named Charles, means lower temperature.  Air
goes into the carb at, say, 55F and is sped up in the venturi.
> The temperature of the air drops to 30F at which point any moisture in the
air will condense out and freeze into ice.  If the ice starts to
> build up, you end up with the problem called carb icing.
>
> The idea that carb icing is most serious from 50F to 70F is drummed into
the head of any student pilot, since airplanes have manual
> carburator heat controls.  Part of the landing checklist is to turn on the
carb heat as you approach the runway so that the carb won't ice
> up during the descent and then not respond with power if the pilot decides
to go around.
>
> On my '71 (with dubious heat riser condition), use the hot air tube and
wire the flap in the "hot" position during the mild SoCal winter.  This
> improves drivability and I haven't had any icing problems.  If I were
running a higher compression engine I'd be very sensitive to
> detonation, as the hotter intake air could cause it.  On my MexiMotor this
isn't a problem at all.
>
> George Lyle
>
> The cure for this is either to heat the part of the carb and intake
manifold to melt the ice, or to heat the intake air so that icing conditions
> are never created.  VW uses both of these approaches on carbed engines,
but on a single Weber conversion the heat riser isn't present.  I
> don't think that there is much icing problems with dual webers since the
intake manifolds are short and heated directly by the heads.
>
